nk about that.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying library setup**\\n\\nI’m considering that if the library has optional components, a deterministic setup might require adding extra dependencies if the target library needs to be used effectively on its own, like slf4j binding or a database driver. In this case, hoplite-core is structured as a core library with separate parser modules. Luckily, the core already includes a built-in Java properties parser and MapPropertySource, which simplifies things a bit for setup.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"no_action\",\n  \"summary\": \"hoplite-core is usable on its own for meaningful tests: the resolved artifact already brings Kotlin reflect/stdlib and coroutines, and core includes MapPropertySource, system/environment property sources, decoders, and the built-in Java .properties parser. Optional format modules are only needed for YAML/JSON/TOML/HOCON examples.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"No environment variables or system properties are required. For file-loading coverage, use MapPropertySource/InputStreamPropertySource or built-in .properties/.props parsing; do not base tests on YAML/JSON/TOML/HOCON unless an optional Hoplite parser module is intentionally added.\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"The README's getting-started examples often use YAML, but YAML requires the optional hoplite-yaml module and is not required to cover hoplite-core.\",\n    \"If generated tests exercise environment/system-property resolvers, they should set and clear those values inside the test to avoid order-dependent behavior.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0305aa7668493a00016a42167a269c8194b229b5efcae950e4\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 3336, "output": 993, "cacheRead": 25088, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 29417, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cache